recordings.loc: Finnie Rd, Fox Township, Kendall County, Illinois
recordings.file-name: XC650721-CERW (M1) - Aberrant Song, Flight Calls - Finnie Rd - 2021-05-21 05_44 Combined.mp3
recordings.rmk:
Two cuts from the same male, singing what is apparently an Orange-crowned Warbler song after first light. In the first cut, he is singing and calling directly overhead in a black walnut, approximately 30ft/9m above ground. In the second cut, he was singing approximately 60ft/18m above ground in a different black walnut. In fact, each time I observed this individual, he was singing in a black walnut.

Before dawn, this same individual could be heard singing the typical Cerulean song. At dawn, this bird switched to singing this aberrant song exclusively. If I had not seen him well singing directly overhead, I would never have guessed that the sounds came from a Cerulean. Also note the buzzy flight calls in the first cut, which are typical of Cerulean Warblers and unlike anything given by Orange-crowned Warblers (or other species that have similarly-structured songs like Nashville Warbler or Wilson's Warbler).

The volume of each individual song changes with the bird's position and direction as it forages in the canopy.

recordings.loc: Mississippi Palisades State Park (near  Savanna), Carroll, Illinois
recordings.rmk: Two cuts from the same mated male, singing the same two-parted (rather than three-parted) song. The neighboring male in the forest on the other side of the street was singing a three-parted song. High in the canopy at all times (at least 40ft above ground), the song volume changes with the bird's position and the direction it was facing relative to the microphone. A single "tink" call is given at 02:44, and at the very end of the recording, some very soft raspy sounds can be heard while the male chased away a second bird of unknown species (I of course cannot be certain that the rasps were given by the CERW or the bird being chased away).

recordings.rmk: A total of six vocalizations given by two birds (one presumed CERW, one presumed NOPA), neither of which I saw well enough to identify visually: chip, chip, buzz, buzz, chip, buzz. The second and fifth are from what I believe is a Northern Parula (either the male in XC420729 or its mate; I cannot be certain). The remainder are consistent with CERW, perhaps given by the male on the adjacent territory? Given the date, habitat, and the birds seen/heard in the area, CERW seems the logical identification.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural Sound. Bird foraging 4-6m above the ground in the forest understory mostly in White Oak trees. Some songs notably Parula-like. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: New Kensington, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania
Doodletown Road, Bear Mountain, Rockland, New York
recordings.rmk: This is one of the coolest warbler encounters I've ever had. A group of male Cerulean Warblers keep up a constant chorus. One or two birds are close-up, while others sing in response in the background. There are probably at least 3 or 4 birds. There is so much sound from one species it reminds me of a chorus of frogs or insects. The chorus is punctuated by songs and calls of Red-bellied Woodpecker, Black-and-white Warbler, and American Redstart. Cerulean Warblers were heard at other spots but I've never heard anything like this.
